EPISTLE 111.-AD J ULIUM FLORUM.

A letter to Julius Florus, to inquire after old friends associated with him in attendance upon Tiberius, who then bad a command in the East3 written also to encourage him in liter-ary and intellectual studies ; but mainly, perhaps, to draw him to a complete reconciliation with a common friend, Munatius.

1. Of Julius Florus nothing is certainly known. Walckenaer conjectures that ho may have been a younger son of Aquilius Florus, slain with his eldest son in the proscription. Torrentius infers from the praenomen that he was a provincial, enfranchised, and adopted into the Julia. qens.
